# JavaScript – Error Handling

---

## 📘 Why Error Handling?

Without error handling, a single runtime error crashes the entire script. Proper error handling makes apps **resilient** and gives users/developers meaningful feedback.

---

## 🧱 try / catch / finally

```js
try {
  // Code that might throw an error
  const result = JSON.parse("invalid json");
} catch (error) {
  // Runs if an error is thrown in try
  console.error("Something went wrong:", error.message);
} finally {
  // ALWAYS runs — with or without an error
  console.log("Cleanup done");
}
```

### The Error Object
```js
try {
  null.name;  // TypeError
} catch (e) {
  e.name      // "TypeError"
  e.message   // "Cannot read properties of null"
  e.stack     // full stack trace (for debugging)
}
```

